{"title_page": "1899 in science", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1899|science}}\n\nThe year '''1899 in [[science]]''' involved some significant events, listed below.\n\n==Astronomy==\n* December 2 \u2013 During the [[new moon]], a near-grand [[conjunction (astronomy and astrology)|conjunction]] of the [[naked-eye planet|classical planets]] and several [[binoculars|binocular]] [[Solar System]] bodies occur. The Sun, Moon, [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], [[Mars]] and [[Saturn]] are all within 15\u00b0 of each other, with [[Venus]] 5\u00b0 ahead of this conjunction and [[Jupiter]] 15\u00b0 behind. Accompanying the classical planets in this grand conjunction are [[Uranus]] (technically visible unaided in [[air pollution|pollution]]-free skies), [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] and [[2 Pallas|Pallas]].\n* The 80&nbsp;cm [[refracting telescope]] is completed at [[Potsdam Observatory]].\n\n==Biology==\n* May 1 \u2013 The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in the [[United Kingdom]] acquires its first part of [[Wicken Fen]], making it the country's oldest [[wetland]] [[nature reserve]].\n* November 8 \u2013 The [[Wildlife Conservation Society|New York Zoological Society]] opens the [[Bronx Zoo|Bronx Zoological Park]] to the public in [[New York City]] under the direction of [[William Temple Hornaday]].\n\n==Chemistry==\n* [[Actinium]] is discovered by [[Andre-Louis Debierne]].\n* [[Commission on Isotopic Abundances and Atomic Weights|International Committee on Atomic Weights]] established.\n\n==Exploration==\n* January 23 \u2013 The British [[Southern Cross Expedition]] crosses the [[Antarctic Circle]]. Later in the year, it first charts [[Duke of York Island (Antarctica)|Duke of York Island]].\n\n==Mathematics==\n* [[\u00c9lie Cartan]] first defines the [[exterior derivative]] in its modern form.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cartan|first=\u00c9lie|title=Sur certaines expressions diff\u00e9rentielles et le probl\u00e8me de Pfaff|journal=Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure|series=S\u00e9rie 3|volume=16|pages=239\u2013332|publisher=Gauthier-Villars|location=Paris|year=1899|language=French|url=http://www.numdam.org/item?id=ASENS_1899_3_16__239_0|issn=0012-9593|jfm=30.0313.04|format=PDF|accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n* [[David Hilbert]] publishes ''[[Grundlagen der Geometrie]]'', proposing a formal set, [[Hilbert's axioms]], to replace [[Euclid's elements]].\n* [[Georg Alexander Pick]] publishes his [[Pick's theorem|theorem]] on the area of [[simple polygon]]s.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Crilly|title=50 Mathematical Ideas you really need to know|location=London|publisher=Quercus|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84724-008-8|page=113}}</ref>\n\n==Medicine==\n* [[Bubonic plague]] enters [[Brazil]] through the seaport of [[Santos (S\u00e3o Paulo)|Santos]].\n* March 6 \u2013 [[Felix Hoffmann]] patents [[Aspirin]] and [[Bayer]] registers its name as a trademark.\n* October 2 \u2013 The [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] is established by [[Patrick Manson]] at the [[Albert Dock Seamen's Hospital]].\n\n==Physics==\n* [[Ernest Rutherford]] classifies two types of [[radioactive decay|radiation]], [[alpha ray]]s and [[beta ray]]s.\n* [[Henri Becquerel]] discovers that radiation from [[uranium]] consists of charged particles and can be deflected by [[magnetic field]]s.\n* [[Hertha Ayrton]] becomes the first woman to read her own paper (on the [[electric arc]]) before the [[Institution of Electrical Engineers]] in [[London]], of which soon afterwards she is elected the first female member.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archives Biographies: Hertha Ayrton|publisher=[[Institution of Engineering and Technology]]|url=http://www.theiet.org/about/libarc/archives/biographies/ayrtonh.cfm|accessdate=2011-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826124515/http://www.theiet.org/about/libarc/archives/biographies/ayrtonh.cfm|archive-date=2010-08-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Technology==\n* February 14 \u2013 [[Voting machine]]s are approved by the [[Congress of the United States|U.S. Congress]] for use in federal [[election]]s.\n* [[Hugo Lentz|Hugo Lenz]] first demonstrates Lenz [[poppet valve]] gear, for [[stationary steam engine]]s.\n* The world's first successful self-propelled steam [[fire engine]], the 'Fire King', is built by [[Merryweather & Sons]] in London and dispatched to [[Port Louis]] on [[Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Ron|last=Henderson|title=Fire King|journal=Vintage Spirit|issue=103|date=February 2011|pages=30-34}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Copley Medal]]: [[Lord Rayleigh]]\n* [[Wollaston Medal|Wollaston Medal for Geology]]: [[Charles Lapworth]]\n\n==Births==\n* January 12 \u2013 [[Paul Hermann M\u00fcller]] (died [[1965 in science|1965]]), [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[chemist]], winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] in [[1948 in science|1948]].\n* February 27 \u2013 [[Charles Herbert Best|Charles Best]] (died [[1978 in science|1978]]), [[United States|American]]-born medical scientist.\n* April 11 \u2013 [[Percy Lavon Julian]] (died [[1975 in science|1975]]), African American research chemist.\n* April 28 \u2013 [[Mary Loveless]], n\u00e9e Hewitt (died [[1991 in science|1991]]), American immunologist.\n* May 8 \u2013 [[Charles Illingworth]] (died [[1991 in science|1991]]), [[English people|English]] [[surgeon]].\n* July 3 \u2013 [[Ludwig Guttmann]] (died [[1980 in science|1980]]), German-born [[neurologist]] and pioneer of paralympic games.\n* July 7 \u2013 [[Anna Baetjer]] (died [[1984 in science|1984]]), American [[toxicologist]].\n* July 26 \u2013 [[Bill Hamilton (engineer)|Bill Hamilton]] (died [[1978 in science|1978]]), [[New Zealand]] [[mechanical engineer]].\n* September 3 \u2013 [[Frank Macfarlane Burnet]] (died [[1985 in science|1985]]), Australian [[Virology|virologist]] best known for his contributions to [[immunology]], winner of the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in [[1960 in science|1960]].\n* September 29 \u2013 [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 B\u00edr\u00f3]] (died 1985), [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] [[List of inventors|inventor]].\n* October 18 \u2013 [[Janet Vaughan]] (died [[1993 in science|1993]]), English [[physiologist]].\n* October 27 \u2013 [[Nikolay Dollezhal]] (died [[2000 in science|2000]]), a key figure in Soviet atomic bomb project and chief designer of nuclear reactors.\n* November 10 \u2013 [[Helen Porter]] (died [[1987 in science|1987]]), English plant physiologist.\n\n==Deaths==\n* January 4 \u2013 [[Henry Alleyne Nicholson]] (born [[1844 in science|1844]]), [[Great Britain|British]] [[Paleontology|palaeontologist]] and [[Zoology|zoologist]].\n* February 18 \u2013 [[Sophus Lie]] (born [[1842 in science|1842]]), [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[mathematician]].\n* March 18 \u2013 [[Othniel Charles Marsh]] (born [[1831 in science|1831]]), American [[paleontologist]].\n* July 16 \u2013 [[Margaretta Riley]] (born [[1804 in science|1804]]), British botanist.\n* August 9 \u2013 [[Edward Frankland]] (born [[1825 in science|1825]]), [[English people|English]] [[chemist]].\n* August 16 \u2013 [[Robert Bunsen]] (born [[1811 in science|1811]]), [[Germany|German]] [[chemist]], perfector of the [[bunsen burner]].\n* October 28 \u2013 [[Ottmar Mergenthaler]] (born [[1854 in science|1854]]), [[German American]] inventor.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1899 in science| ]]\n[[Category:19th century in science]]\n[[Category:1890s in science]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year nav topic5|1899|science}}\n\nThe year '''1899 in [[science]]''' involved some significant events, listed below.\n\n==Astronomy==\n* December 2 \u2013 During the [[new moon]], a near-grand [[conjunction (astronomy and astrology)|conjunction]] of the [[naked-eye planet|classical planets]] and several [[binoculars|binocular]] [[Solar System]] bodies occur. The Sun, Moon, [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]], [[Mars]] and [[Saturn]] are all within 15\u00b0 of each other, with [[Venus]] 5\u00b0 ahead of this conjunction and [[Jupiter]] 15\u00b0 behind. Accompanying the classical planets in this grand conjunction are [[Uranus]] (technically visible unaided in [[air pollution|pollution]]-free skies), [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] and [[2 Pallas|Pallas]].\n* The 80&nbsp;cm [[refracting telescope]] is completed at [[Potsdam Observatory]].\n\n==Biology==\n* May 1 \u2013 The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] in the [[United Kingdom]] acquires its first part of [[Wicken Fen]], making it the country's oldest [[wetland]] [[nature reserve]].\n* November 8 \u2013 The [[Wildlife Conservation Society|New York Zoological Society]] opens the [[Bronx Zoo|Bronx Zoological Park]] to the public in [[New York City]] under the direction of [[William Temple Hornaday]].\n\n==Chemistry==\n* [[Actinium]] is discovered by [[Andre-Louis Debierne]].\n* [[Commission on Isotopic Abundances and Atomic Weights|International Committee on Atomic Weights]] established.\n\n==Exploration==\n* January 23 \u2013 The British [[Southern Cross Expedition]] crosses the [[Antarctic Circle]]. Later in the year, it first charts [[Duke of York Island (Antarctica)|Duke of York Island]].\n\n==Mathematics==\n* [[\u00c9lie Cartan]] first defines the [[exterior derivative]] in its modern form.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cartan|first=\u00c9lie|title=Sur certaines expressions diff\u00e9rentielles et le probl\u00e8me de Pfaff|journal=Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure|series=S\u00e9rie 3|volume=16|pages=239\u2013332|publisher=Gauthier-Villars|location=Paris|year=1899|language=French|url=http://www.numdam.org/item?id=ASENS_1899_3_16__239_0|issn=0012-9593|jfm=30.0313.04|format=PDF|accessdate=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n* [[David Hilbert]] publishes ''[[Grundlagen der Geometrie]]'', proposing a formal set, [[Hilbert's axioms]], to replace [[Euclid's elements]].\n* [[Georg Alexander Pick]] publishes his [[Pick's theorem|theorem]] on the area of [[simple polygon]]s.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Crilly|title=50 Mathematical Ideas you really need to know|location=London|publisher=Quercus|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84724-008-8|page=113}}</ref>\n\n==Medicine==\n* [[Bubonic plague]] enters [[Brazil]] through the seaport of [[Santos (S\u00e3o Paulo)|Santos]].\n* March 6 \u2013 [[Felix Hoffmann]] patents [[Aspirin]] and [[Bayer]] registers its name as a trademark.\n* October 2 \u2013 The [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] is established by [[Patrick Manson]] at the [[Albert Dock Seamen's Hospital]].\n\n==Physics==\n* [[Ernest Rutherford]] classifies two types of [[radioactive decay|radiation]], [[alpha ray]]s and [[beta ray]]s.\n* [[Henri Becquerel]] discovers that radiation from [[uranium]] consists of charged particles and can be deflected by [[magnetic field]]s.\n* [[Hertha Ayrton]] becomes the first woman to read her own paper (on the [[electric arc]]) before the [[Institution of Electrical Engineers]] in [[London]], of which soon afterwards she is elected the first female member.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archives Biographies: Hertha Ayrton|publisher=[[Institution of Engineering and Technology]]|url=http://www.theiet.org/about/libarc/archives/biographies/ayrtonh.cfm|accessdate=2011-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826124515/http://www.theiet.org/about/libarc/archives/biographies/ayrtonh.cfm|archive-date=2010-08-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Technology==\n* February 14 \u2013 [[Voting machine]]s are approved by the [[Congress of the United States|U.S. Congress]] for use in federal [[election]]s.\n* [[Hugo Lentz|Hugo Lenz]] first demonstrates Lenz [[poppet valve]] gear, for [[stationary steam engine]]s.\n* The world's first successful self-propelled steam [[fire engine]], the 'Fire King', is built by [[Merryweather & Sons]] in London and dispatched to [[Port Louis]] on [[Mauritius]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Ron|last=Henderson|title=Fire King|journal=Vintage Spirit|date=February 2011|pages=30-34}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Copley Medal]]: [[Lord Rayleigh]]\n* [[Wollaston Medal|Wollaston Medal for Geology]]: [[Charles Lapworth]]\n\n==Births==\n* January 12 \u2013 [[Paul Hermann M\u00fcller]] (died [[1965 in science|1965]]), [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[chemist]], winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] in [[1948 in science|1948]].\n* February 27 \u2013 [[Charles Herbert Best|Charles Best]] (died [[1978 in science|1978]]), [[United States|American]]-born medical scientist.\n* April 11 \u2013 [[Percy Lavon Julian]] (died [[1975 in science|1975]]), African American research chemist.\n* April 28 \u2013 [[Mary Loveless]], n\u00e9e Hewitt (died [[1991 in science|1991]]), American immunologist.\n* May 8 \u2013 [[Charles Illingworth]] (died [[1991 in science|1991]]), [[English people|English]] [[surgeon]].\n* July 3 \u2013 [[Ludwig Guttmann]] (died [[1980 in science|1980]]), German-born [[neurologist]] and pioneer of paralympic games.\n* July 7 \u2013 [[Anna Baetjer]] (died [[1984 in science|1984]]), American [[toxicologist]].\n* July 26 \u2013 [[Bill Hamilton (engineer)|Bill Hamilton]] (died [[1978 in science|1978]]), [[New Zealand]] [[mechanical engineer]].\n* September 3 \u2013 [[Frank Macfarlane Burnet]] (died [[1985 in science|1985]]), Australian [[Virology|virologist]] best known for his contributions to [[immunology]], winner of the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in [[1960 in science|1960]].\n* September 29 \u2013 [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 B\u00edr\u00f3]] (died 1985), [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] [[List of inventors|inventor]].\n* October 18 \u2013 [[Janet Vaughan]] (died [[1993 in science|1993]]), English [[physiologist]].\n* October 27 \u2013 [[Nikolay Dollezhal]] (died [[2000 in science|2000]]), a key figure in Soviet atomic bomb project and chief designer of nuclear reactors.\n* November 10 \u2013 [[Helen Porter]] (died [[1987 in science|1987]]), English plant physiologist.\n\n==Deaths==\n* January 4 \u2013 [[Henry Alleyne Nicholson]] (born [[1844 in science|1844]]), [[Great Britain|British]] [[Paleontology|palaeontologist]] and [[Zoology|zoologist]].\n* February 18 \u2013 [[Sophus Lie]] (born [[1842 in science|1842]]), [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[mathematician]].\n* March 18 \u2013 [[Othniel Charles Marsh]] (born [[1831 in science|1831]]), American [[paleontologist]].\n* July 16 \u2013 [[Margaretta Riley]] (born [[1804 in science|1804]]), British botanist.\n* August 9 \u2013 [[Edward Frankland]] (born [[1825 in science|1825]]), [[English people|English]] [[chemist]].\n* August 16 \u2013 [[Robert Bunsen]] (born [[1811 in science|1811]]), [[Germany|German]] [[chemist]], perfector of the [[bunsen burner]].\n* October 28 \u2013 [[Ottmar Mergenthaler]] (born [[1854 in science|1854]]), [[German American]] inventor.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1899 in science| ]]\n[[Category:19th century in science]]\n[[Category:1890s in science]]\n", "name_user": "Camboxer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTechnology:ref improved", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1899_in_science"}
{"title_page": "Calamus viminalis", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = viminalis\n|authority = [[Carl Ludwig Willdenow |Willd.]], Sp. Pl., ed. 4 [Willdenow] 2(1): 203 (1799).<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus viminalis Willd. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665477-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus buroensis'' [[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]] ex [[Wilhelm Gerhard Walpers|Walp.]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus viminalis Willd. |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/665477-1#synonyms |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew/Science |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. extensus'' Mart.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' [[William Roxburgh|Roxb.]]\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''andamanicus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''bengalensis'' Becc.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''cochinchinensis'' Becc.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''pinangianus'' Becc.\n*''C. litoralis'' [[Carl Ludwig Blume|Blume]]\n*''C. phuocbinhensis'' [[Andrew Henderson|A.J.Hend.]] & N.Q.Dung\n*''C. pseudorotang'' Mart.\n*''C. siamensis'' Becc.\n*''C. siamensis'' var. ''malaianus'' Furtado\n*''C. viminalis'' var. ''fasciculatus'' (Roxb.) Becc.\n*''Palmijuncus fasciculatus'' (Roxb.) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]\n*''P. litoralis'' (Blume) Kuntze\n*''P. pseudorotang'' (Mart.) Kuntze\n*''P. viminalis'' (Willd.) Kuntze\n*''Rotang viminalis'' (Willd.) Baill.</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Calamus viminalis''''', one of many Calamus species commonly called rattan, is a plant species native to: [[Java]] and [[Bali]] in [[Indonesia]]; [[Peninsular Malaysia]]; all parts of [[Thailand]]; [[Cambodia]]; [[Cochinchina]] and Central [[Annam]] in [[Vietnam]]; all parts of [[Laos]]; [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands; North-east, North-central, and [[South India]]; and probably North-west and South [[Yunnan]] in [[China]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nIt grows at village margins and in scrub, forest edge and (locally) inside evergreen forest, from 0-600m elevation.<ref name=\"powo\"/>. IN Cambodia it occurs in semi-dense forests and at the rear of mangrove formations.<ref name=\"DyPhon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh|page=499-500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q10901207}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|viminalis]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1799]]\n[[Category:Flora of India (region)]]\n[[Category:Flora of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Flora of Myanmar]]\n\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = viminalis\n|authority = [[Carl Ludwig Willdenow |Willd.]], Sp. Pl., ed. 4 [Willdenow] 2(1): 203 (1799).<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus viminalis Willd. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/665477-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *<small>''Calamus buroensis'' [[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]] ex [[Wilhelm Gerhard Walpers|Walp.]]<ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus viminalis Willd. |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/665477-1#synonyms |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew/Science |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''C. extensus'' Mart.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' [[William Roxburgh|Roxb.]]\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''andamanicus'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''bengalensis'' Becc.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''cochinchinensis'' Becc.\n*''C. fasciculatus'' subvar. ''pinangianus'' Becc.\n*''C. litoralis'' [[Carl Ludwig Blume|Blume]]\n*''C. phuocbinhensis'' [[Andrew Henderson|A.J.Hend.]] & N.Q.Dung\n*''C. pseudorotang'' Mart.\n*''C. siamensis'' Becc.\n*''C. siamensis'' var. ''malaianus'' Furtado\n*''C. viminalis'' var. ''fasciculatus'' (Roxb.) Becc.\n*''Palmijuncus fasciculatus'' (Roxb.) [[Carl Ernst Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]\n*''P. litoralis'' (Blume) Kuntze\n*''P. pseudorotang'' (Mart.) Kuntze\n*''P. viminalis'' (Willd.) Kuntze\n*''Rotang viminalis'' (Willd.) Baill.</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Calamus viminalis''''', one of many Calamus species commonly called rattan, is a plant species native to: [[Java]] and [[Bali]] in [[Indonesia]]; [[Peninsular Malaysia]]; all parts of [[Thailand]]; [[Cambodia]]; [[Cochinchina]] and [[Central Annam]] in [[Vietnam]]; all parts of [[Laos]]; [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands, [[North-east]], [[North-central]], and [[South India]]; and probably North-west and [[South Yunnan]] in [[China]].<ref name=\"powo\" />\n\nIt grows at village margins and in scrub, forest edge and (locally) inside evergreen forest, from 0-600m elevation.<ref name=\"powo\"/>. IN Cambodia it occurs in semi-dense forests and at the rear of mangrove formations.<ref name=\"DyPhon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh|page=499-500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=665477}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|viminalis]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1799]]\n[[Category:Flora of India (region)]]\n[[Category:Flora of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Flora of Myanmar]]\n\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brunswicknic", "label": "safe", "comment": "link work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calamus_viminalis"}
{"title_page": "Caroline Sampson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Caroline Sampson\n| image         =Miss Sampson.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date |1984|08|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tema]], Ghana\n| nationality   = Ghanaian\n| education     = [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]]\n| alma_mater    = African University College of Communication\n| occupation    = [[Broadcast journalist]], [[Radio personality]], [[TV Personality]] \n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for     = [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]], [[TV3 Ghana|TV3]], ETV Ghana, Citi FM, Atlantis Radio, Yfm , Kwese TV\n| notable_works = ''Continuous Drive and Mellow Cruise,'' ''U-Win Game Show,'' Hitz Video, E on E , Citi FM\u2019s Room 973, Shout on Y\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n}}\n\n'''Caroline Sampson'''  (born 2 August 1984), is a Ghanaian radio presenter, TV show host, a compere and a voice over artist best known for her TV and Radio commercials. She began her career in the media in 2005 when she ended up as a finalist in the third edition of the [[Ghanaian]] reality TV pageant [[Miss Malaika Ghana]].\n\nAside the TV and radio presenting, Caroline has hosted reality TV shows, corporate events and other movie premieres and album launches. She was the first anglophone African and Ghanaian to win the award for Best Presenter at the Stars Integration of Culture of Africa festival & competition held in Benin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Female-Ghanaian-celebrities-that-came-out-of-Beauty-Pageants-374975|title=Female Ghanaian celebrities that came out of Beauty Pageants|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nanabkay.blogspot.com/2015/11/my-hero-caroline-sampson-tells-her.html|title=Welcome To Nana Bekoe's Blog: My Hero - Caroline Sampson Tells Her Story of a Decade of Showbiz on Twitter|date=9 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2019}}\nCaroline Sampson was born in Tema at the Valco Hospital on August 2, 1984 and grew up in [[Tema]] Community 7. She is the only child of her mother Madam Mary Araba Quarshie and her father Mr Jacob Maxwell Apraku Sampson. Caroline was educated at the Creator Preparatory School in Tema where she had her primary school and junior high school education. She then went on to study General Arts at [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]]. \n\nWhile there, Caroline loved to dance and participated in a lot of activities, performing and hosting shows in and outside campus. She was also an executive for Writers, Drama and Debaters Club (WDDC) and GUNSA for the academic year 2002. She had her tertiary education at the African University College of Communications (AUCC).\n\n==Career==\n===Modeling===\nSampson's career began as a contestant in the third edition of the TV reality show, Miss Malaika Ghana, in 2005. She placed among the final 16 contestants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/bi/lifestyle/ghanaian-female-celebrities-who-were-in-beauty-pageant-id5319279.html|title=Ghanaian celebrities that you didn't realize competed in beauty pageants|first=Nathan|last=Tollo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201511/260345.php|title=10 Years of Caroline Sampson In Showbiz|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nIn 2005, Sampson got her first break on television when she hosted the game show, ''U-Win Game,'' that aired on [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]] (Ghana National Broadcaster). Later, she hosted ''Hitz Video'', a weekly music video program that aired on the [[TV3 Ghana]] network.\n\nIn 2009, Sampson joined Global Media Alliance, the parent company of ETV and YFM Ghana;  and hosted ''E on E,'' a daily entertainment show on ETV Ghana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/caroline-sampson-bring-ladies-together-girlfriends-saturday/|title=Caroline Sampson to bring the ladies together with 'Girlfriends' this Saturday - AmeyawDebrah.Com|date=4 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/entertainment/celebrity/caroline-marks-10-years-in-radio.html|title=Caroline marks 10 years in radio|first=Ann|last=Dzasah|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she moved to Kwese Sport as a host of the station's breakfast show, ''Head Start''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.citifmonline.com/2017/04/06/kwese-free-sports-premieres-brand-new-local-productions-in-april/|title=Kwes\u00e9 Free Sports Premieres Brand New Local Productions in April - Citi Sport|website=sport.citifmonline.com}}</ref> and later became host of a sport program, ''Sports Arena '' on the same channel.\n\n===Radio===\nIn 2005, while working with [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]], Sampson also began working in radio on the Atlantis radio station in [[Accra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/caroline-sampson-dines-with-fans-on-vals-day/|title=Caroline Sampson dines with fans on Vals Day - News Ghana|website=www.newsghana.com.gh}}</ref> She hosted two daily drive-time shows, ''Continuous Drive'' and ''Mellow Cruise''. Sampson joined Citi FM and hosted three daily shows: ''Room 973'', ''Rhythms in the Citi'' and ''Citi Countdown''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Citi-FM-s-Caroline-Gives-Birth-To-A-Baby-Boy-202311|title=Citi FM\u2019s Caroline Gives Birth To A Baby Boy!|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Is-Zigi-The-Father-of-Caroline-Sampson-s-Baby-222305|title=Is Zigi The Father of Caroline Sampson's Baby?|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> After two years with Citi FM, Sampson joined YFM Ghana as a presenter for the weekly show, ''Shout on Y''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Caroline-Sampson-quits-YFM-heads-to-Joy-FM-543511|title=Caroline Sampson quits YFM; heads to Joy FM|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201808/359406.php|title=From Haemorrhoids To Cataract To Fibroids & Cervical polyps\u2026 TV Personality Caroline Sampson Shares Her Struggles|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/YFM-s-Caroline-Sampson-bounced-at-passport-office-because-her-dress-was-short-533203|title=YFM\u2019s Caroline Sampson bounced at passport office because her dress was short?|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Brand ambassador==\nIn 2017, Sampson and Ghanaian rapper, [[Kofi Kinaata]], were brand ambassadors for beverage company [[Guinness]] Ghana. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/27/kofi-kinaata-and-caroline-sampson-announced-as-guinness-osagyefo-ambassadors/|title=Kofi Kinaata and Caroline Sampson Announced as Guinness Osagyefo Ambassadors|first=YFM|last=Ghana|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kasapafmonline.com/2017/03/20/jay-foley-kofi-kinaata-caroline-sampson-now-brand-influencers-guinness/|title=Jay Foley, Kofi Kinaata, Caroline Sampson now Brand Influencers for Guinness \u2013 Kasapa102.5FM|website=kasapafmonline.com}}</ref> She also was brand ambassador for Woodin (fabric company),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/woodin-unveils-ama-k-abebrese-caroline-sampson-m-anifest-and-dj-black-as-ambassadors/|title=Woodin unveils Ama K Abebrese, Caroline Sampson, M.anifest and DJ Black as ambassadors - AmeyawDebrah.Com|date=1 October 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanacelebrities.com/2012/09/30/photos-ama-k-abebrese-dj-black-manifest-caroline-sampson-named-as-brand-ambassadors-as-woodin-re-launched-in-accra/|title=Ama K. Abebrese, DJ Black, Manifest & Caroline Sampson Named As Brand Ambassadors As Woodin Re-Launched In Accra|website=www.ghanacelebrities.com}}</ref> and was also the face of beverage company [[Castle Milk Stout]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/castle-milk-stout-makes-caroline-sampson-as-its-new-face/|title=Castle Milk Stout Makes Caroline Sampson As {{sic|It|\u2019s|nolink=y}} New Face - News Ghana|website=www.newsghana.com.gh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201412/224583.php|title=PHOTO: Caroline Sampson Spotted With Her Cute Son|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref>\nCaroline is also a social media influencer and has endorsed brands such as Zeepay, Huawei and World Remit, among others.<ref>https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/30/y-fms-caroline-sampson-to-speak-at-2017-young-achievers-summit/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCaroline Sampson won Best Presenter in 2009 at the Stars Integration of Culture of Africa held in Cotonou, Benin. In 2019, she won Best Female Radio Personality at the 3rd edition of Ghana Entertainment Awards USA. She also received the 4th XWAC-Africa Award of Honour for Media Excellence in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/blog.article.php?blog=1603&ID=1000004805|title=GhanaWeb Blog: Caroline Sampson Wins Award At SICA 2009|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/20/yfms-caroline-sampson-and-dj-mic-smith-nominated-for-ghana-naija-showbiz-awards/|title=YFM\u2019s Caroline Sampson and DJ Mic Smith nominated for Ghana-Naija Showbiz Awards|first=YFM|last=Ghana|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sampson, Caroline}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tema]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian journalists]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian radio presenters]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Caroline Sampson\n| image         =Miss Sampson.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date |1984|08|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tema]], Ghana\n| nationality   = Ghanaian\n| education     = [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]]\n| alma_mater    = African University College of Communication\n| occupation    = [[Broadcast journalist]], [[Radio personality]], [[TV Personality]] \n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for     = [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]], [[TV3 Ghana|TV3]], ETV Ghana, Citi FM, Atlantis Radio, Yfm , Kwese TV\n| notable_works = ''Continuous Drive and Mellow Cruise,'' ''U-Win Game Show,'' Hitz Video, E on E , Citi FM\u2019s Room 973, Shout on Y\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n}}\n\n'''Caroline Sampson'''  (born 2 August 1984), is a Ghanaian radio presenter, TV show host, a compere and a voice over artist best known for her TV and Radio commercials. She began her career in the media in 2005 when she ended up as a finalist in the third edition of the [[Ghanaian]] reality TV pageant [[Miss Malaika Ghana]].\n\nAside the TV and radio presenting, Caroline has hosted reality TV shows, corporate events and other movie premieres and album launches. She was the first anglophone African and Ghanaian to win the award for Best Presenter at the Stars Integration of Culture of Africa festival & competition held in Benin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Female-Ghanaian-celebrities-that-came-out-of-Beauty-Pageants-374975|title=Female Ghanaian celebrities that came out of Beauty Pageants|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nanabkay.blogspot.com/2015/11/my-hero-caroline-sampson-tells-her.html|title=Welcome To Nana Bekoe's Blog: My Hero - Caroline Sampson Tells Her Story of a Decade of Showbiz on Twitter|date=9 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2019}}\nCaroline Sampson was born in Tema at the Valco Hospital on August 2, 1984 and grew up in [[Tema]] Community 7. She is the only child of her mother Madam Mary Araba Quarshie and her father Mr Jacob Maxwell Apraku Sampson. Caroline was educated at the Creator Preparatory School in Tema where she had her primary school and junior high school education. She then went on to study General Arts at [[Mfantsiman Girls' Secondary School]]. \n\nWhile there, Caroline loved to dance and participated in a lot of activities, performing and hosting shows in and outside campus. She was also an executive for Writers, Drama and Debaters Club (WDDC) and GUNSA for the academic year 2002. She had her tertiary education at the African University College of Communications (AUCC).\n\n==Career==\n===Modeling===\nSampson's career began as a contestant in the third edition of the TV reality show, Miss Malaika Ghana, in 2005. She placed among the final 16 contestants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/bi/lifestyle/ghanaian-female-celebrities-who-were-in-beauty-pageant-id5319279.html|title=Ghanaian celebrities that you didn't realize competed in beauty pageants|first=Nathan|last=Tollo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201511/260345.php|title=10 Years of Caroline Sampson In Showbiz|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nIn 2005, Sampson got her first break on television when she hosted the game show, ''U-Win Game,'' that aired on [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]] (Ghana National Broadcaster). Later, she hosted ''Hitz Video'', a weekly music video program that aired on the [[TV3 Ghana]] network.\n\nIn 2009, Sampson joined Global Media Alliance, the parent company of ETV and YFM Ghana;  and hosted ''E on E,'' a daily entertainment show on ETV Ghana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/caroline-sampson-bring-ladies-together-girlfriends-saturday/|title=Caroline Sampson to bring the ladies together with 'Girlfriends' this Saturday - AmeyawDebrah.Com|date=4 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/entertainment/celebrity/caroline-marks-10-years-in-radio.html|title=Caroline marks 10 years in radio|first=Ann|last=Dzasah|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she moved to Kwese Sport as a host of the station's breakfast show, ''Head Start''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.citifmonline.com/2017/04/06/kwese-free-sports-premieres-brand-new-local-productions-in-april/|title=Kwes\u00e9 Free Sports Premieres Brand New Local Productions in April - Citi Sport|website=sport.citifmonline.com}}</ref> and later became host of a sport program, ''Sports Arena '' on the same channel.\n\n===Radio===\nIn 2005, while working with [[GTV (Ghana)|GTV]], Sampson also began working in radio on the Atlantis radio station in [[Accra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/caroline-sampson-dines-with-fans-on-vals-day/|title=Caroline Sampson dines with fans on Vals Day - News Ghana|website=www.newsghana.com.gh}}</ref> She hosted two daily drive-time shows, ''Continuous Drive'' and ''Mellow Cruise''. Sampson joined Citi FM and hosted three daily shows: ''Room 973'', ''Rhythms in the Citi'' and ''Citi Countdown''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Citi-FM-s-Caroline-Gives-Birth-To-A-Baby-Boy-202311|title=Citi FM\u2019s Caroline Gives Birth To A Baby Boy!|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Is-Zigi-The-Father-of-Caroline-Sampson-s-Baby-222305|title=Is Zigi The Father of Caroline Sampson's Baby?|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> After two years with Citi FM, Sampson joined YFM Ghana as a presenter for the weekly show, ''Shout on Y''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Caroline-Sampson-quits-YFM-heads-to-Joy-FM-543511|title=Caroline Sampson quits YFM; heads to Joy FM|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201808/359406.php|title=From Haemorrhoids To Cataract To Fibroids & Cervical polyps\u2026 TV Personality Caroline Sampson Shares Her Struggles|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/YFM-s-Caroline-Sampson-bounced-at-passport-office-because-her-dress-was-short-533203|title=YFM\u2019s Caroline Sampson bounced at passport office because her dress was short?|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Brand ambassador==\nIn 2017, Sampson and Ghanaian rapper, [[Kofi Kinaata]], were brand ambassadors for beverage company [[Guinness]] Ghana. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/27/kofi-kinaata-and-caroline-sampson-announced-as-guinness-osagyefo-ambassadors/|title=Kofi Kinaata and Caroline Sampson Announced as Guinness Osagyefo Ambassadors|first=YFM|last=Ghana|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kasapafmonline.com/2017/03/20/jay-foley-kofi-kinaata-caroline-sampson-now-brand-influencers-guinness/|title=Jay Foley, Kofi Kinaata, Caroline Sampson now Brand Influencers for Guinness \u2013 Kasapa102.5FM|website=kasapafmonline.com}}</ref> She also was brand ambassador for Woodin (fabric company),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/woodin-unveils-ama-k-abebrese-caroline-sampson-m-anifest-and-dj-black-as-ambassadors/|title=Woodin unveils Ama K Abebrese, Caroline Sampson, M.anifest and DJ Black as ambassadors - AmeyawDebrah.Com|date=1 October 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanacelebrities.com/2012/09/30/photos-ama-k-abebrese-dj-black-manifest-caroline-sampson-named-as-brand-ambassadors-as-woodin-re-launched-in-accra/|title=Ama K. Abebrese, DJ Black, Manifest & Caroline Sampson Named As Brand Ambassadors As Woodin Re-Launched In Accra|website=www.ghanacelebrities.com}}</ref> and was also the face of beverage company [[Castle Milk Stout]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsghana.com.gh/castle-milk-stout-makes-caroline-sampson-as-its-new-face/|title=Castle Milk Stout Makes Caroline Sampson As It\u2019s New Face - News Ghana|website=www.newsghana.com.gh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/news/201412/224583.php|title=PHOTO: Caroline Sampson Spotted With Her Cute Son|first=Peace FM|last=Online|publisher=}}</ref>\nCaroline is also a social media influencer and has endorsed brands such as Zeepay, Huawei and World Remit, among others.<ref>https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/30/y-fms-caroline-sampson-to-speak-at-2017-young-achievers-summit/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCaroline Sampson won Best Presenter in 2009 at the Stars Integration of Culture of Africa held in Cotonou, Benin. In 2019, she won Best Female Radio Personality at the 3rd edition of Ghana Entertainment Awards USA. She also received the 4th XWAC-Africa Award of Honour for Media Excellence in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/blog.article.php?blog=1603&ID=1000004805|title=GhanaWeb Blog: Caroline Sampson Wins Award At SICA 2009|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yfmghana.com/2017/03/20/yfms-caroline-sampson-and-dj-mic-smith-nominated-for-ghana-naija-showbiz-awards/|title=YFM\u2019s Caroline Sampson and DJ Mic Smith nominated for Ghana-Naija Showbiz Awards|first=YFM|last=Ghana|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sampson, Caroline}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tema]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian journalists]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian radio presenters]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBrand ambassador:add sic template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline_Sampson"}
